sionary sites," where questions of global inequality, transnational religious fellowship, and postcolonial cultural and economic forces are negotiated.   A nuanced critique of the ambivalent relationships among religion, capitalism, and humanitarian aid, Conversionary Sites draws important connections between religion and science, capitalism and charity, and the US and the Global South.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aFaith-based human serviceszMadagascar. 0aFaith-based human serviceszMinnesota. 0aMedical assistance, AmericanzMadagascar. 0aMissions, MedicalxSocial aspects. 0aMissions, MedicalzMadagascar. 4aChristianity. 4aColonialism. 4aFaith based aid. 4aGlobal medicine. 4aHumanitarianism. 4aMadagascar. 4aMedical relief. 4aUnited States. 4aValue. 4aWaste economies. 70(DE-601)1062276020(DE-588)4039567-4aMission2gnd 70(DE-601)1063168340(DE-588)4020775-4aGesundheitswesen2gnd 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226557434423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226557434.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles